Instead of using the `<marquee>` tag, you can achieve similar effects with CSS animations which are widely supported and provide better control over the animation.

Here's a very basic example of how you might use CSS to create a scrolling effect:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
@keyframes scroll {
    0% { transform: translateX(100%); }
    100% { transform: translateX(-100%); }
}

.marquee {
    white-space: nowrap;
    overflow: hidden;
    box-sizing: border-box;
    background-color: #aea;
    display: block;
    width: 100%; /* This can be adjusted to fit your needs */
    animation: scroll 5s linear infinite;
}

.marquee p {
    display: inline-block;
    padding-left: 100%; /* Make sure the content is off-screen initially */
    margin: 0;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="marquee">
    <p>This is a scrolling text example using CSS animations.</p>
</div>

</body>
</html>
```

This is just a starting point. You can customize the animation speed, direction, delay, and more by adjusting the CSS. Remember that CSS animations are more versatile, efficient, and consistent across different web environments.

